ff68697d-d397-4d48-8f9d-92fb8a6723ef.a6ad32ea-de93-4745-938e-d5087b174826.description=
This operation does not do anything. It can be used to filter flow variables by defining them as inputs and filtering them in the Results tab.

Inputs\:
    field1 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field2 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field3 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field4 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of  "field1" as it was specified at input or when filtered. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
ff68697d-d397-4d48-8f9d-92fb8a6723ef.ab25d16f-5472-45fd-9158-6f3434d23993.prompt=${folder_creation} ff68697d-d397-4d48-8f9d-92fb8a6723ef.ab53dc3c-9829-43ac-8ba3-0eda6e167fa4.description=Counts from one number to another number. 
Inputs\:
from - The number to start counting at.
to - The number to count to.
incrementBy - The number to increment by while counting. If unspecified this is 1. If you wanted to count 2,4,6,8 this would be 2.
reset - If true, then the counter will restart counting from the beginning.

NOTE\: These values must be between -9223372036854775808 and 9223372036854775807

Returns\:
The number that was just counted.

Note\: the primary result is resultString, Result can also be used. result (All lower case) should not be used as it is the response code.

Responses\:
has more - Not yet done counting.
no more - Done counting. This will only be returned once, then counting restarts.
failure - Something went wrong.
ff68697d-d397-4d48-8f9d-92fb8a6723ef.af131510-996b-494f-84a1-97530c7416a6.prompt=Give the host of the destination file\: ff68697d-d397-4d48-8f9d-92fb8a6723ef.b6d11302-9dff-4cfc-8310-95d3a78976a5.prompt=DownloadLocation ff68697d-d397-4d48-8f9d-92fb8a6723ef.b719580f-e1f6-42a9-b61e-6dee212aac84.description=
This operation copies files between two remote machines using different protocols (local, SCP, FTP, SFTP or SMB).

Inputs\:
    sourceHost - The host of the source file.
    sourcePort - The port for connecting to the source host.
    sourceUsername - The username for connecting to the host of the source file.
    sourcePassword - The password for connecting to the host of the source file.
    sourcePrivateKeyFile - Absolute path of the private key file for public/private key authentication on the source host.
    sourcePath - The absolute path to the source file. In case of FTP or SFTP protocol please use a relativ path to FTP/SFTP server root directory.
    sourceProtocol - The protocol used to copy from the source file.
Valid values\: local, SCP, FTP, SFTP or SMB. 
    sourceCharacterSet - The name of the control encoding to use with source host for FTP and SFTP protocols. 
Examples\: UTF-8, EUC-JP, SJIS.  
Default\: for FTP, the default is ISO-8859-1 (Latin1). For SFTP, it is UTF-8.
    destinationHost - The host of the destination file.
    destinationPort - The port for connecting to the destination host.
    destinationUsername - The username for connecting to the host of the destination file.
    destinationPassword - The password for connecting to the host of the destination file.
    destinationPrivateKeyFile - Absolute path of the private key file for public/private key authentication on the destination host.
    destinationPath - The absolute path to the destination file.
    destinationProtocol - The protocol used to copy to the destination file.
Valid values\: local, SCP, FTP, SFTP or SMB.
    destinationCharacterSet - The name of the control encoding to use with destination host for FTP and SFTP protocols. 
Examples\: UTF-8, EUC-JP, SJIS.   
Default\: for FTP, the default is ISO-8859-1 (Latin1). For SFTP, it is UTF-8.
    fileType - The type of the file being copied if using FTP. This input must be empty if FTP protocol is not used.
Valid values\: binary, ascii.
Default value\: binary
    passive - If true, passive connection mode will be enabled if using FTP.
Valid values\: true, false.
Default value\: false

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output and contains the "Copy completed successfully" message if operation successfully completes, or an exception message otherwise.
    returnCode - It is 0 if operation successfully completes, -1 otherwise.
    exception - It contains an exception message if something went wrong.

Responses\:
    success - The file was copied successfully.
    failure - The file could not be copied.

Examples\:
1. The following is a valid inputs example for copying a file from a Windows machine to a  Linux machine\:
        sourceHost\: server1.example.com
        sourcePort\: 22
        sourceUsername\: username1
        sourcePasword\: password1
        sourcePath\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        sourceProtocol\: scp
        destinationHost\: server2.example.com
        destinationPort\: 22
        destinationUsername\: username2
        destinationPassword\: password2
        destinationPath\: /root/example.txt
        destinationProtocol\: scp
2. The following is a valid inputs example for copying a file from a Linux machine to a Windows machine\:
        sourceHost\: server2.example.com
        sourcePort\: 22
        sourceUsername\: username2
        sourcePasword\: password2
        sourcePath\: /root/example.txt
        sourceProtocol\: scp
        destinationHost\: server1.example.com
        destinationPort\: 22
        destinationUsername\: username1
        destinationPassword\: password1
        destinationPath\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        destinationProtocol\: scp
3. The following is a valid inputs example for copying a file from a Linux machine to a Windows machine without prerequisites\:
        sourceHost\: server2.example.com
        sourcePort\: 22
        sourceUsername\: username2
        sourcePasword\: password2
        sourcePath\: /root/example.txt
        sourceProtocol\: scp
        destinationHost\: server1.example.com
        destinationUsername\: username1
        destinationPassword\: password1
        destinationPath\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        destinationProtocol\: smb

ff68697d-d397-4d48-8f9d-92fb8a6723ef.ee94307f-b1fb-4bcb-80ae-110959fc7b44.description=
This operation checks whether a string matches another string, using a specific matching rule. The "toMatch" input is the string that is checked for matching the "matchTo" expression. 

Inputs\:
    matchType - The type of match to perform.
Valid values\: Exact Match, Contains, Contains Once, Does Not Contain, Match All Words, Match No Words, Regex
Default value\: Exact Match
    toMatch - The string that is checked for matching.
    matchTo - The string to match against.
Example\: If "matchType" is “RegEx”, the "matchTo" input is a regular expression such as\: ^-?\d+(([\.,]\d+)?)+$. 
    ignoreCase - Specifies whether to ignore case when matching or not.
Valid values\: False, True
Default value\: False

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the string "Matches" if the "toMatch" string matches the "matchTo" string. Otherwise, it contains the string "Does Not Match".  

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.
